DOM (Document Object Model) is a tree structure of HTML elements. JavaScript allows you to interact with and modify the DOM dynamically.

Selecting Elements:
1. getElementById():
   const element = document.getElementById('myId');

2. querySelector() (CSS selector):
   const element = document.querySelector('.myClass');
   const allElements = document.querySelectorAll('p');

3. getElementsByClassName():
   const elements = document.getElementsByClassName('myClass');

4. getElementsByTagName():
   const elements = document.getElementsByTagName('p');

Creating & Removing Elements:
1. Create element:
   const newDiv = document.createElement('div');

2. Add text content:
   newDiv.textContent = 'Hello World';
   // OR
   newDiv.innerHTML = '<p>Hello</p>';

3. Append to parent:
   document.body.appendChild(newDiv);
   // OR
   parentElement.appendChild(newDiv);

4. Remove element:
   element.remove();
   // OR
   parentElement.removeChild(element);

Modifying Attributes:
1. Get attribute:
   const value = element.getAttribute('data-id');

2. Set attribute:
   element.setAttribute('class', 'newClass');
   element.setAttribute('data-id', '123');

3. Remove attribute:
   element.removeAttribute('class');

4. Direct property access:
   element.id = 'newId';
   element.className = 'myClass';
   element.textContent = 'New text';

Modifying Styles:
1. Inline styles:
   element.style.color = 'red';
   element.style.fontSize = '16px';
   element.style.backgroundColor = 'blue';

2. CSS classes (better practice):
   element.classList.add('active');
   element.classList.remove('inactive');
   element.classList.toggle('visible');
   element.classList.contains('active'); // returns true/false

Traversing the DOM:
1. Parent element:
   const parent = element.parentElement;
   const parentNode = element.parentNode;

2. Child elements:
   const children = element.children; // HTMLCollection
   const childNodes = element.childNodes; // NodeList
   const firstChild = element.firstElementChild;
   const lastChild = element.lastElementChild;

3. Sibling elements:
   const nextSibling = element.nextElementSibling;
   const prevSibling = element.previousElementSibling;

Event Handling:
1. Add event listener:
   element.addEventListener('click', function(event) {
     console.log('Element clicked');
   });

2. Common events:
   - 'click': Mouse click
   - 'dblclick': Double click
   - 'mouseover': Mouse enters element
   - 'mouseout': Mouse leaves element
   - 'keydown': Keyboard key pressed
   - 'keyup': Keyboard key released
   - 'input': Form input value changed
   - 'change': Form element value changed
   - 'submit': Form submitted
   - 'focus': Element receives focus
   - 'blur': Element loses focus
   - 'scroll': Page/element scrolled
   - 'load': Page/image loaded

3. Event object:
   element.addEventListener('click', function(event) {
     console.log(event.target); // Element that triggered event
     console.log(event.type); // Event type
     event.preventDefault(); // Stop default behavior
     event.stopPropagation(); // Stop event bubbling
   });

Form Manipulation:
1. Get input value:
   const value = document.getElementById('input').value;

2. Set input value:
   document.getElementById('input').value = 'New value';

3. Check checkbox/radio:
   const isChecked = document.getElementById('checkbox').checked;

4. Get select value:
   const selectedValue = document.getElementById('select').value;

5. Form submission:
   const form = document.getElementById('myForm');
   form.addEventListener('submit', function(event) {
     event.preventDefault();
     // Handle form data
   });

DOM Manipulation Best Practices:
1. Cache element selections:
   const button = document.getElementById('btn');
   // Use button multiple times

2. Batch DOM changes:
   // Instead of multiple appends, use fragment
   const fragment = document.createDocumentFragment();
   fragment.appendChild(div1);
   fragment.appendChild(div2);
   element.appendChild(fragment);

3. Use textContent instead of innerHTML when not inserting HTML:
   element.textContent = 'Safe text';

4. Delegate events (for dynamic elements):
   document.addEventListener('click', function(event) {
     if (event.target.matches('.dynamic-class')) {
       // Handle click
     }
   });

5. Remove old listeners to avoid memory leaks:
   element.removeEventListener('click', myFunction);

Common Patterns:
1. Toggle visibility:
   element.classList.toggle('hidden');

2. Add/remove multiple classes:
   element.className = 'class1 class2 class3';

3. Loop through elements:
   document.querySelectorAll('p').forEach(function(element) {
     element.style.color = 'blue';
   });

4. Conditional styling:
   if (element.classList.contains('active')) {
     element.style.display = 'block';
   }

5. Create and style element:
   const div = document.createElement('div');
   div.className = 'card';
   div.textContent = 'Content';
   document.body.appendChild(div);
